1. Create the Common DTOs Module
Create a new Maven module:
In your parent project, create a new module named common-dtos
Set the packaging type to jar in pom.xml:
xml
<packaging>jar</packaging>
Configure pom.xml:
Use spring-boot-dependencies as the parent (not spring-boot-starter-parent)
Add only the necessary dependencies (validation, lombok, etc.)
No need for Spring Boot starters or Eureka client dependencies
2. Define Your DTOs
Create DTO classes in the common-dtos module:
Example: CardRequest.java, CardResponse.java
Use Lombok annotations for clean code
Add validation annotations if needed
Example DTO:
java
@Schema(description = "Request object for creating/updating a card")
public record CardRequest(
    @NotBlank String cardNumber,
    @NotBlank String cardType,
    @Positive double creditLimit,
    @NotNull Long customerId
) {}
3. Build and Install
Build the module:
bash
mvn clean install
This will install the JAR in your local Maven repository.
4. Use in Microservices
Add dependency in your service's pom.xml:
xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.java.from.scratch</groupId>
    <artifactId>common-dtos</artifactId>
    <version>0.0.1-SNAPSHOT</version>
</dependency>
Use the DTOs in your controllers and services:
java
@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<CardResponse> createCard(@Valid @RequestBody CardRequest request) {
    // Implementation
}
5. Important Notes
Keep it simple:
Only include shared DTOs, enums, and utility classes
